        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: 'Without self-discipline, planning an offensive against an outside enemy is easier than realizing a single goal, a simple truth that Jocko Willink has distilled throughout his years in the military. In our bodies fight for homeostasis, they sometimes play games with our minds. But we cannot force ourselves to change because we secretly want the old and familiar order. That is the reason our biggest enemy is ourselves. We want to become better versions of who we are but are not ready to face the challenges.\n\nWillink argues that deep within ourselves, we are strong-willed. We have to become the personal strict mentor who attacks all our fears before they attack us, without relying on short spurts of inspiration. We are strong enough to recycle negative feedback or circumstance into fuel to move forward and achieve goal after goal.\n\nPhysical training and a healthy diet are the ultimate challenges we encounter in one way or another. In Willink philosophy, they are a chance to set a foundation for further victories. Even sleep can become a weapon if we learn to use it to our advantage. All it takes is a decision. In other words, we cannot compromise with the demons in our heads telling us to take a rest. We may deserve it, but it will not do us much good.\n\nEither way, life is a strategy with free choices and actions. One thing to keep in mind. No one will win our battles for us.\n\nA small exercise to try. Develop a joyous morning routine, so you will want to wake up early. Inspiration develops in the process of doing. Start working and watch yourself get engaged. Find a role model with a similar background or values to give you a perspective of the future you want.'
